You have allocated Rs. 50 billion for the Ministry of Urban Development and Housing. But, how many areas in my District come under that Ministry? For those districts to become urban areas, first, you need to work on connectivity and make sure there is accessibility. We do

not have bridges. Out of the Rs. 50 billion that has been allocated, give out at least 10 per cent to my District. Then, we can create a few more cities, urban areas. But, you all are not happy to do that. That is why we want you to devolve power. Give us power. Then, we will do it.

We have been talking about devolution of power in this country for years, for decades. Why? Because we want to develop our people; we want to give our people a better future. There may be the subject Minister of the Central Government. But, obviously, the Minister and the State Minister will end up spending most of this money on their own electorates or helping their friends. Friends mean, the other Ministers or the State Ministers. So, when do we develop our areas? Should we not give the people of the North and the East a developed economy?

Under that Ministry, there is a department called the Department of Government Factories. For that Department, there is an allocation of Rs. 50 million as Capital Expenditure. Today, Rs. 50 million is peanuts! How can you develop the Department of Government Factories with a Capital Expenditure of just Rs. 50 million? It is mostly likely to paint the building.

They can come up with new proposals to conserve those areas. If you all cannot do it, give us the power and we will show you how it is done. For example, if we take taxation, even a five-star hotel which comes under the purview of the provincial council is taxed the same amount as that of a house in extent of 100 square metres or 200 square metres. Taxation for all constructions in that area is the same. Why can that not be changed? We can make the necessary laws to suit our areas. Maybe, a law that suits Unawatuna does not suit us; a law that suits Negombo does not suit us. Why are you all scared to give us the power to make laws to suit our areas? Why are you scared?

Hon. Minister, we have a labour law in this country, but the estate companies are practising a different law. They act as if the estates belong to them. So, I think, you should take action against them because it is a serious issue now. Not only - [Interruption.] Okay, I undertstand. Thank you, Hon. Minister. , .
, . , , . , , ; they do not have to pay EPF and ETF. So, they are taking in labourers on a daily basis. , . , . . , .

Hon. Minister, I think you know that a survey done recently shows that 56.8 per cent of our population are willing to migrate, that they want to leave here and go to some other country. Nationally, it is 56.8 per cent, but among the younger generation, among those between 18 to 29 years, it is 77.2 per cent. What is the reason for that? The youngsters do not have hope, belief or confidence in their future in this country. I think the Government has failed to address the unemployment issue in this Budget. Today, it is very evident that a higher number of passports are being issued to the youths and they are fleeing the country. I think it is not a good sign for a country like Sri Lanka which has one of the highest literacy rates in Asia. So, we should look into this seriously and take action because the youth are our future leaders. I think, as lawmakers, we should adopt visionary policies to gain back the confidence of the youths. That is the most important thing. Migration is not a solution. Our youths, our pool of knowledge or our human resource leaving the country is not a good sign.

Finally, I just want to say one more thing. Another recent survey shows that a Sri Lankan worker's salary is going to get reduced by 20.5 per cent next year, in 2023. It is only behind that of Argentina, which is going to get reduced by 26 per cent. Even in Pakistan, it is going to get reduced only by 9.9 per cent. So, it is a serious issue. We are well behind even Pakistan. At the same time, if you consider the salaries of other Asian Countries, our neighbour and closest friend, India, is much ahead. India, who always helps us in times of crisis, is on top of the list with a salary increase of 4.6 per cent, followed by Vietnam with a 4 per cent increase and China, with a 3.8 per cent increase. So, the rising inflation, underemployment as well as migration are serious issues. Therefore, I think we all should get together, take serious note of those and take our country forward. Once again, I would say that we should safeguard our youth and our future generation. Thank you.
